<TEXT>
the only nuclear plant ever shut down because 
control room operators slept on duty is ready to resume operations 
amid signs that the nuclear regulatory commission will give its 
assent 
an nrc order has kept the peach bottom plant in pennsylvania 
dormant for two years but the commission planned a meeting for 
this afternoon along with a possible vote on reopening 
privately commission officials said last week that all signs 
pointed to the plant gaining permission if not today then 
shortly afterward to begin a slow ascension that would take it 
back to full power 
thomas murley the nrcs top reactor licensing official 
declined to make a prediction friday on the outcome of the meeting 
but he said in an interview that the commission has seen 
significant progress in the management of the plant by philadelphia 
electric co 
clearly there have been big changes in the company and its a 
new company as far as peach bottom is concerned murley said 
the operators have been retrained and there appears to be a new 
attitude 
as the only plant ever shut down because of operator negligence 
peach bottom is unique in the industry dealing with operators 
with people is vastly different than replacing equipment and the 
shutdown has meant a review of the plants entire management 
structure 
the plant located on the susquehanna river near the maryland 
border was ordered to stop producing power on march 31 1987 by 
the nrc which said continued operation posed a public safety 
threat 
a year later james l everett stepped down as the utilitys 
chairman and chief executive officer following criticism of the 
handling of peach bottom 
philadelphia electric has spent about 250 million in 
shutdownrelated costs the figure includes modifications to the 
plant purchases of replacement power and the companys share of a 
125 million fine the largest in nrc history 
while the utility has shuffled its personnel the changes at the 
plant have included more than just new faces the company said 
management will play a broader role in daytoday plant affairs 
than before 
to end catnaps by operators plant officials replaced 
comfortable highbacked chairs in the control room with lowbacked 
models operators rotations have been changed so that workers do a 
week of days followed by a week of an afternoonevening shift and 
then work the overnight 
the rotation which includes days off used to go in the reverse 
order 
the sleeping problems at peach bottom were not confined to a few 
workers last august 33 present or former operators were fined 
500 to 1000 for sleeping andor other acts of inattention to 
duty 
we didnt set out to pick somebody and make an example of 
them murley said its just that the behavior we saw at peach 
bottom was so egregious that we felt we had no choice but to order 
them shut down inpo the institute for nuclear power operations 
came to same conclusion and put more pressure on the top 
management 
inpo an atlantabased nuclear watchdog group termed the plant 
an embarrassment to the industry and the nation in 1988 
but this year the group said philadelphia electrics corrective 
actions at peach bottom have been responsive and effective 
the utility said it would propose restarting one of its two 
working reactors then seek permission to fire up the other one 
later this year it would take a few months for either of the units 
to reach full power once approval is granted 
</TEXT>
