uruguayans on sunday voted not to end 
an amnesty for soldiers and police accused of human rights abuses 
during the 197385 military dictatorship 
with 6360 of 7072 districts reporting in the referendum on the 
1986 amnesty supporters tallied 922185 votes or 5332 percent 
according to the interior ministry and while opponents numbered 
678087 or 3921 percent 
about 128969 votes or 747 percent were blank annulled or 
ruled questionable for technical reasons 
early today a copresident of the national commission for a 
referendum conceded defeat 
the law has been confirmed matilde rodriguez larreta told 
reporters without doubt the pronouncement of the popular will 
should be adhered to 
however she called for a national compromise on the issue 
and said about 40 percent voted to annul the law the 
country and all its institutions cannot be insensitive to the 
circumstances that nearly onehalf of the population disagrees 
radically with the amnesty 
unofficial tallies indicated that voters in the capital narrowly 
rejected the amnesty while voters in the countryside heavily 
favored it 
shortly after polls closed at 730 pm 630 pm edt and 
before any results were known president julio m sanguinetti 
called for national unity in an address carried on national radio 
and television 
until a short while ago some of us were yellows others 
greens he said that has just ended we are all 
uruguayan citizens and now we have to listen to the voice of the 
people 
supporters of the amnesty cast yellow ballots opponents cast 
green ones 
the government including sanguinetti supported the 1986 law 
giving amnesty to scores of police and soldiers accused of human 
rights abuses in a campaign against leftist guerrillas during 12 
years of military rule 
leftist political parties and human rights groups which mounted 
a huge petition drive to put the issue to a vote say trials of 
those accused of human rights abuses are necessary before democracy 
can be considered fully restored 
after campaigning ended on thursday both sides pledged to 
respect the outcome 
by late sunday night neither side had claimed victory or 
conceded defeat 
were still gathering information and making our own 
computations said alberto perez perez a spokesman for the 
national commission for a referendum the interior ministry 
estimated that about 65 percent of the 23 million uruguayans 
eligible to vote had cast ballots 
voting is mandatory in uruguay and turnout usually tops 80 
percent turnout apparently was lower than usual sunday because of 
gray skies and rain 
but lines were long from the moment schools cultural centers 
movie theaters and other places used as polling stations opened 
many voters waited for an hour or longer huddled under umbrellas or 
building overhangs 
