welldressed woman standing in line to vote in a neighborhood along 
the estuary of the river plate a future of peace and justice 
depend on overturning the amnesty said the woman who refused to 
give her name 
if voters rejected the amnesty trials would not start 
immediately vice president enrique tarigo said the supreme court 
then would have to decide whether the amnesty would be annulled 
meaning a ruling that it never legally existed or merely 
overturned 
if the law were just overturned the change could not be applied 
retroactively 
the amnesty freed security forces from the possibility of 
prosecution in connection with a 1970s crackdown on leftist 
subversion about 150 uruguayans were killed and 200 were arrested 
and never seen again thousands suffered physical and psychological 
torture under detention 
the military maintains it was fighting a war against urban 
guerrillas particularly the leftist tupamaros whose bombings 
kidnappings and assassinations had convulsed the country for years 
the military took control in february 1973 by setting up a 
security council with the authority to veto government decisions 
four months later it forced president juan m bordaberry to 
dissolve congress 
the tupamaro urban guerrillas by that time had been quelled as a 
military threat and the armed forces began to crack down on 
leftist subversion in general 
sanguinetti was elected in november 1984 after democracy was 
restored 
by 1986 about 50 cases had been filed accusing about 180 
soldiers and police of kidnapping murder and torture 
the military high command said it would not require soldiers to 
answer charges in civilian courts sanguinetti broke the impasse by 
pressing for an amnesty which congress passed on dec 22 1986 
human rights and leftist political groups vowed to challenge the 
amnesty in a vote the electoral court last year affirmed that the 
required 555701 voters or 25 percent of the electorate had 
signed petitions for a referendum 
