<DOCNO> AP890417-0062 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to settle some 
key questions involving the ability of multinational corporations 
to challenge state taxes in federal court 
what the justices decide sometime next year in a california case 
could carry bigmoney significance for most states and many big 
businesses 
the court granting an appeal by california officials said they 
will review a ruling that allowed two multinational corporations to 
challenge a state tax in federal court 
in a 1984 ruling seen as a major victory for states the 
justices ruled that california may tax multinational corporations 
based on the businesses worldwide income 
but that decision applied only to multinationals whose parent 
company is located in the united states 
the case acted on today involves multinationals whose parent 
company is based in a foreign country 
californias business tax the same levy upheld in the 1984 
ruling was challenged by alcan aluminium limited a canadian 
corporation and imperial chemical industries plc a british 
corporation 
california taxed subsidiaries of the multinationals doing 
business in the state 
the california tax employs what is known as the unitary system 
the method bases the tax on a share of worldwide earnings payroll 
and property value of each multinational and its subsidiaries 
at issue in the appeal acted on today is whether multinationals 
based abroad have legal standing to challenge such unitary state 
taxes in federal courts in the united states 
alcan and imperial challenged the california tax in a federal 
court in chicago where the california franchise tax board has an 
office 
a federal judge threw out the suits on grounds that the parent 
companies claimed they were injured only in their capacity as 
shareholders of their subsidiaries and therefore lacked legal 
standing 
generally shareholders are barred from suing in such cases 
unless they can demonstrate a direct and independent injury 
from the corporation 
the 7th us circuit court of appeals last october overturned 
the judges decision againt alcan and imperial reinstating their 
suits the appeals court said there is grounds for the parent 
companies to assert a direct and independent injury 
shareholders with direct personal interests in a cause of 
action can bring suit even if the corporations legal rights and 
obligations are also implicated the appeals court said 
the asserted injuries to alcan and imperial are direct and 
independent the appeals court said because the unitary tax 
diminishes the attractiveness of owning american subsidiaries in 
comparison with entering into contracts with independent companies 
as a means of engaging in foreign commerce 
the appeals court added the potential for the unitary tax to 
penalize foreign ownership of american assets distinguishes it 
from other forms of state regulation environmental or safety 
rules for example that would presumably affect foreign and 
domestically owned operations fairly equally 
the appeals court said taxes like the one imposed by california 
have fueled a simmering trade controversy which has raised 
concerns about foreign retaliation and the united states ability 
to speak with one voice on matters of foreign commerce 
most states and the multistate tax commission joined in 
supporting californias appeal 
the commission said the 7th circuit court rulings effect is to 
permit multinational corporations to forum shop around the 
country for a sympathetic federal judge who will permit the 
businesses to challenge the state taxes 
the case is franchise tax board vs alcan aluminium 881400 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890417-0063 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the supreme court in an important banking 
industry case today asked the bush administration for its view on 
whether us banks with branch offices overseas must pay depositors 
after foreign governments seize or freeze those accounts 
the court invited justice department lawyers to comment on 
rulings that required citibank to pay depositors 
the justices are not expected to say whether they will grant 
full review to the case until hearing from the government lawyers 
which could take months 
robert h bork a former federal judge whose supreme court 
nomination was defeated by the senate in 1987 is representing 
citibank 
if the court were to grant review bork might become the first 
defeated nominee in the courts history to later argue a case 
before the justices 
in the appeal acted on today bork said billions of dollars are 
at stake there are more than 900 branches of us banks operating 
in 73 countries with some 225 billion in deposits 
the cases acted on today stem from the fall of saigon vietnam 
to the vietcong in 1975 and economic troubles in the philippines in 
1983 
the vietnamese case involves an account at citibanks saigon 
office opened in 1974 by quang quy trinh a retired south 
vietnamese government official 
the account which paid annual interest of 19 percent compounded 
daily was for trinhs son ngoc quang trinh a student in michigan 
at the time 
the deposit agreement between trinh and citibank said the bank 
did not accept responsibility for any loss due to government 
orders laws or from any other cause beyond its control 
citibank closed its saigon branch on april 24 1975 on the eve 
of the citys fall to communist troops 
the elder trinh was placed in a reeducation camp by the new 
regime and after he was released in 1980 sent the citibank 
passbook to his son in michigan 
the younger trinh sued the bank to recover the deposits 
the 6th us circuit court of appeals last july upheld a ruling 
that citibank must pay trinh 319636 including 179269 in 
interest 
the appeals court rejected citibanks argument that its deposit 
agreement excused it from paying deposits lost because of political 
revolution 
the agreement the elder trinh signed did not mean he was aware 
that he had given up his right to proceed against the home office 
of citibank in the event the branch was no longer in existence 
and could not pay its depositors the appeals court said 
it added that both trinh and citibank are innocent parties in 
the case but one must suffer a loss 
in the philippines case wells fargo asia limited in singapore 
deposited 2 million with the citibank branch in manila in june 
1983 the money was to be repaid with interest six months later 
but on oct 15 1983 the philippine government of ferdinand 
marcos who was deposed and fled to hawaii in 1986 froze the 
accounts of foreign banks the move prevented citibank from 
repaying the manila deposits to wells fargo 
wells fargo sued to recover the money and citibank later paid 
it 934000 citibank withheld the balance of the original deposit 
a federal judge in 1987 ordered citibank to repay the balance in 
1987 and the 2nd us circuit court of appeals upheld the ruling 
last july 
the appeals court relied on an agreement between the two banks 
that suggested citibanks home office in new york city had the duty 
to pay the money 
the cases are citibank vs trinh 881031 and citibank vs 
wells fargo 881260 
</TEXT>
