<TEXT>
lech walesa still gives the impression 
that he could be spending his days repairing electric carts at the 
lenin shipyard 
instead he is usually to be found negotiating with the interior 
minister meeting with foreign heads of state and leading the 
solidarity movement that has changed his countrys course 
the story of walesa scaling the shipyard fence to inspire 
strikers in forming the east blocs first independent trade union 
is often repeated but should not lose its significance poland has 
not been the same since that day in august 1980 
walesa 45 has never lost the authenticity with which he drew 
millions to his vision of workers solidarity 
on monday he chalked up his latest victory leading solidarity 
through seven years of repressions to regain its legal status just 
as he vowed to do 
the winner of the nobel peace prize a man of deep roman 
catholic faith intended to travel to rome on wednesday to thank 
polishborn pope john paul ii for the churchs role in helping to 
bring about the agreement with authorities 
walesa wears a suit and tie these days but always with a 
picture of the black madonna of czestochowa icon and a solidarity 
pin on his lapel he usually also sports a us vicepresidential 
tie pin given him by george bush in 1987 
but he remains a modest person often answering his home 
telephone himself and riding the early morning train from gdansk on 
his frequent trips to warsaw for highlevel meetings with polish 
authorities 
when in warsaw he stays in a small cloister cell at the church 
episcopate after a long night of negotiations he sometimes 
travels the four hours back to gdansk to sleep in his own bed 
complaining of a bad cold he decided to stay in gdansk on 
monday when a court in warsaw formally registered solidarity again 
as a legal trade union independent of the government 
walesas autocratic leadership style bothers some in the union 
and although he is a spellbinding orator his statements to 
reporters can sometimes be as cryptic as an oracles pronouncements 
a natural politician who goes with his gut walesa ignored 
warnings that he was giving in too easily in september when he put 
his reputation with workers on the line by ending a series of 
strikes nationwide in return for a vague promise of talks from the 
government 
although some youthful militants chanted down with walesa 
in the months that followed he never seemed to doubt the decision 
many solidarity activists point to walesas convincing showing 
in a nationwide tv debate in october as the turning point that 
brought about the talks which won solidarity its legalization 
walesa apologized for his poor performance 
much has changed in poland during the eight months since the 
august strikes but not walesa 
he marked his conclusion of an historic accord with the 
government on april 5 not at the celebratory cocktail party at a 
government palace but by eating dinner in a nearly deserted hotel 
dining room with an aide 
i am exhausted and i dont like eating standing he said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

