<TEXT>
key events in the history of solidarity 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
aug 14 electrician lech walesa leads occupation strike at 
gdansks lenin shipyard and starts worker revolt against communist 
state 
aug 31 authorities agree to make solidarity the soviet blocs 
only legal independent union during its 16 months of legal 
activity solidarity membership grows to an estimated 10 million 
and a sense of renewal sweeps the nation 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
dec 13 with a general strike threatened gen wojciech 
jaruzelski declares martial law suppressing solidarity activities 
and interning thousands of members including walesa 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
oct 8 solidarity is banned and an official trade union 
alliance created to take its place the united states expands 
economic sanctions against poland 
nov 11 walesa freed 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
july 22 jaruzelski lifts martial law but leaves many 
restrictive edicts 
oct 5 walesa wins nobel peace prize 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
july 21 amnesty is approved for political prisoners including 
11 prominent solidarity leaders jailed after martial law 
oct 19 popular prosolidarity priest the rev jerzy 
popieluszko is slain four state security police will be tried and 
convicted 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
aug 31 walesa accuses government of presiding over a 
political economic and cultural disaster as supporters nationwide 
mark fifth anniversary of solidaritys birth 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
sept 11 the government releases 225 political prisoners 
including all senior solidarity leaders 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
feb 19 last of us sanctions against poland lifted 
nov 29 poles vote in first referendum in 41 years but deny 
government support for economic reform package 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
april 24may 10 strikes hit steel mills shipyards and other 
plants across poland police break up one strike others gradually 
die out 
aug 16 workers declare a strike at july manifesto coal mine 
strikes spread creating polands worst labor strife in seven years 
aug 26 interior minister gen czeslaw kiszczak proposes 
negotiations between the communist government and the 
solidarityled opposition 
aug 31 walesa holds first meeting with government officials 
in six years and appeals to workers to end strikes 
sept 3 strikes end as walesa asks for time to talk with the 
government 
oct 25 talks postponed as government objects to opposition 
participants 
nov 30 walesa and alfred miodowicz head of the official 
union alliance hold live television debate walesas convincing 
performance rekindles plans for talks 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
jan 17 communist party leadership decides solidarity can be 
legalized under certain conditions meeting solidaritys 
prerequisite for talks 
feb 6 the roundtable negotiations begin with the 
government seeking opposition participation in the 
communistdominated political system in exchange for trade union 
freedoms 
april 5 walesa and kiszczak conclude the historic 
deliberations by endorsing a new social contract for polands 
future 
the political and economic reforms include a new senate which 
will be the east blocs first freely elected legislative body and 
the post of president the right to have more than one union at a 
workplace opposition access to the printed and electronic media 
and pricewage indexation 
april 13 first elections to include opposition candidates are 
set for june 4 
monday solidarity is formally registered again as a trade 
union operating independently of the polish government 
</TEXT>
