<TEXT>
a gatekeeper said today he refused 
police orders to open an outer gate and allow thousands of late 
arrivals to pour into a soccer stadium where 94 fans were crushed 
to death fans and officials said police opened the barrier 
south yorkshire police who were in charge of saturdays club 
semifinal at hillsborough stadium came under mounting attack as 
liverpool ordered a week of mourning for victims who came to watch 
the citys team play play nottingham forest 
fans and officials said officers responded inadequately and far 
too slowly when spectators were crushed against a steel antiriot 
fence in a standingroomonly area 
gatekeeper jack stone told the yorkshire post he refused police 
orders to open a 16footwide outer gate survivors said about 
4000 fans outside were pushing at turnstiles 
stone would not confirm survivors reports that police officers 
opened the concertina gate but he told the newspaper you know 
as well as anyone whose fault it was 
liverpool fan stephen mitton told british broadcasting corp 
television the steward put his hand on the gate and said dont 
open it the police said open the gate theres going to be a 
crush then two police officers opened the gate 
new arrivals poured in pressing those inside against the 
10foot fence mounted police herded them into the overcrowded 
center terrace some fans said today 
the crush was so great mitton said that fans fell on the floor 
and people climbed over them all the police were doing was 
standing up saying get back get back there was already people 
dead then i climbed on them to get over the fence 
south yorkshires chief constable peter wright said saturday a 
senior officer decided to open the gates to save peoples lives 
and to relieve the crush outside 
he said he was not aware of any connection between the gate 
being opened and the surge on the standing section where many 
victims died 
one of those being trapped in the front of the terrace stephen 
hendry 19 said people were screaming at the police to open the 
gate at the front of the terrace and three fans managed to climb 
over the fence but no sooner had they got out than one of them was 
thrown back over by a copper 
paul middup a police federation representative said today the 
growing public criticism of police actions was grossly unfair 
they were faced with a situation for which no amount of 
training could prepare them he said 
in parliament today home secretary douglas hurd announced an 
independent inquiry to determine the cause of what prime minister 
margaret thatcher called a disaster of immense proportions 
hurd said major soccer clubs may be told to replace 
standingroom terraces with seats as lawmakers and sports 
officials are demanding 
we owe a duty to these passionate supporters of football 
soccer to examine urgently and thoroughly the causes and 
background and to do all in our power to prevent such a thing 
happening again hurd said we have to set our sights high and 
find a better way for british football 
lord justice taylor will lead the inquiry starting tuesday he 
said 
police released the names of all 94 victims today ranging from 
a 10yearold boy who was trampled and the 67yearold brother of a 
former liverpool soccer player to two sisters who died before their 
fathers eyes 
businessman trevor hicks 43 tried to resuscitate his two 
daughters sarah 19 and victoria 15 after they were pulled from 
the crush of bodies 
football was the one thing we did as a family and now we are 
not a family anymore he said 
all the victims were british thirtyfour were teenagers and 33 
were in their 20s seven were women 
of the 170 injured 47 remained hospitalized today including 17 
in intensive care 
liverpool soccer team members visited some of the injured fans 
as did prince charles and his wife princess diana 
south yorkshire police whose crowdcontrol measures will be at 
the core of the inquiry handed over the police investigation to 
neighboring west midlands police 
authorities will want to determine why thousands of fans still 
were outside as the match began and examine charges that many 
entered the soldout stadium which has a capacity of 54000 with 
forged tickets or no tickets at all 
sir harry livermore a liverpool lawyer and former lord mayor of 
liverpool released a statement from a policeman whom he refused to 
identify calling the police operation disorganized pathetic 
and amateurish 
the liverpool city council today called an official week of 
mourning and discussed ways of helping the bereaved and injured 
it was the third major soccer tragedy in four years involving 
english teams which have been barred from european soccer 
competition since a may 29 1985 rampage by liverpool fans at 
heysel stadium in brussels that killed 39 people 
europes soccer authority last week lifted the ban on english 
clubs playing in europe in the 199091 season pending a review 
next april 
