policy the planning of the operation and the quality of the 
intelligence were not revealed 
it said spanish police who had been involved in tracking the 
three to the gibraltar border did not testify 
spanish testimony could have helped establish whether they were 
known to be without guns or explosives the absence of this 
testimony also made the evidence incomplete the report said 
it said much forensic evidence was destroyed because standard 
procedures were not followed while the state pathologist was 
denied adequate postmortem facilities and ballistics reports 
