<TEXT>
a drug commonly prescribed for sedation and 
relief of cold symptoms is linked to sudden infant death syndrome 
and should not be sold without a prescription a public interest 
research group said monday 
public citizen health research group urged the food and drug 
administration to reverse its decision allowing overthecounter 
sales of the drug known by the trade name phenergan 
overthecounter availability implies fda designation of a 
margin of safety which in this case is not justified said 
andrew holmes and sidney wolfe physicians with the health research 
group in a letter to the fda 
the group filed a petition with the fda four months ago to block 
overthecounter sales of the drug but no action has been taken 
the group said the matter now deserves urgent attention because 
nonprescription doses of the drug are scheduled to reach pharmacy 
shelves in june 
fda spokeswoman susan cruzan said the groups petition is under 
review the agency has 180 days to review such petitions she said 
the fda last august decided that promethazine hydrochloride the 
active ingredient in phenergan could be used in overthecounter 
coughcold products based on the fact there hasnt been a safety 
problem to justify keeping it under prescription when used as 
labeled and it is labeled not for use in children under 6 cruzan 
said 
the drug is a phenothiazine a class of major tranquilizers 
with antihistamine properties that offer some relief from cold 
symptoms by drying the upper airways 
it is manufactured by wyethayerst laboratories company 
spokeswoman audrey ashby said the fda carefully reviewed all 
data before making its decision and was satisfied the products 
are suitable for overthecounter sales she added that in 
their 35 years of marketing these syrups have been remarkably 
problemfree 
but the health group noted that although phenergan is not 
recommended for children under 2 years old doctors wrote 175000 
prescriptions for the drug for that age group in 1985 it is often 
prescribed for children with colic holmes said 
a study in belgium where the drug is available without a 
prescription linked use with sudden infant death syndrome or 
sids and found that it can cause obstruction of infants breathing 
passages during sleep the health group said the study found that 
children who died of sids were 10 times more likely to have been 
given phenergan or a related drug recently than children in a 
control group 
about 5000 infants die of sids each year in the united states 
its cause is unknown but phenergan is believed to be a 
contributing factor the research group said 
even if only a small percentage of the us sids deaths are 
caused by prescription phenergan the increase in such deaths 
expected with otc overthecounter availability adds up to a 
senseless and avoidable tragedy the letter said 
dr richard l naeye chairman of the pathology department at 
the pennsylvania state university college of medicine has done 
extensive research on sids and is one of the six experts who wrote 
the fda supporting the health groups petition he said that while 
studies have not proven a connection between sids and phenergan 
they have found an association between the two that needs more 
study 
its an unresolved issue but i dont think its good to 
resolve it by putting it on the market over the counter he said 
naeye said that while he generally endorses the fdas push to 
make more drugs available without prescription in this case 
its not prudent 
</TEXT>
