<TEXT>
charles kenny ck mcclatchy who 
lambasted some fellow publishers for putting profit over news was 
remembered upon his death as a leader with the very highest 
standards 
the 62yearold editor and chairman of the board of mcclatchy 
newspapers collapsed sunday afternoon while jogging in a park said 
erwin potts president of the company he was pronounced dead a 
short time later at the university medical center apparently of 
heart attack 
potts said mcclatchy had no history of heart problems he was 
a very healthy guy and he took good care of himself its just 
a shock to all of us 
he was a hell of a newspaper man and he was a hell of a guy 
were just going to miss him an awful lot said potts who had 
known mcclatchy for 13 years 
mcclatchy was heir to a news empire that dated to the california 
gold rush 
his familys newspaper group publishes 12 west coast newspapers 
including the sacramento bee the anchorage daily news which won 
this years pulitzer prize for public service the fresno bee and 
the modesto bee and the morning news tribune in tacoma and 
tricity herald in washington state 
tom johnson publisher and chief executive officer of the los 
angeles times called mcclatchy a splendid newspaper leader who 
represented the very highest standards of editorial and managerial 
excellence 
he was uncommonly dedicated to quality in his newspapers 
johnson said his passing is a major loss to our profession 
mcclatchy blasted fellow publishers in a january 1988 speech 
saying many paid more attention to profit margins than quality 
journalism 
he told an audience at the university of california riverside 
that some media groups used their publications as everfaithful 
cash cows for the owners 
ck represents everything that was good about journalism and 
newspapering said gregory favre executive editor of the 
sacramento bee 
his values his concerns his integrity his gentleness and 
his toughness his generosity his intellect his curiousity and 
his caring created an environment which inspired all around him to 
do their best favre said 
howard weaver managing editor of the anchorage daily news said 
that since mcclatchys purchase of the paper a decade ago the 
company provided it financial support to literally go from being 
on its deathbed to being the states leading newspaper 
mcclatchys company became embroiled in a legal dispute in 1984 
with thensen paul laxalt a close friend of ronald reagan and 
onetime republican candidate for president after the sacramento 
bee and two other newspapers in the group published a story in 1983 
on the laxalt familys ownership of a hotelcasino in nevada during 
the 1970s it said federal agents believed someone had illegally 
skimmed profits from the casino to cut its tax liability 
laxalt filed a 250 million libel suit against the mcclatchy 
newspapers when the suit was settled in 1987 the papers issued a 
statement saying extensive discovery found no evidence of 
skimming both sides claimed victory 
mcclatchy born march 25 1927 in fresno earned his 
undergraduate degree at stanford university in 1950 
he served in the army from 1951 to 1953 and reported for the 
washington post from 1953 to 1955 
the next two years he was assistant press secretary to adlai 
stevenson in the democrats second unsuccessful presidential 
campaign against dwight d eisenhower 
in 1957 mcclatchy returned to reporting with abc news in 
washington 
he joined the sacramento bee in 1958 starting as a reporter and 
working his way to associate editor in 1962 
he was named editor of mcclatchy newspapers in 1974 elected 
company president in 1978 replacing his aunt eleanor mcclatchy and 
made chairman in 1988 
in feburary 1988 mcclatchy newspapers offered public stock for 
the first time but control remained under mcclatchy and six other 
family members and several family trusts 
mcclatchy was the greatgrandson of james mcclatchy an irish 
immigrant who came to california in 1857 became a reporter on the 
newly founded sacramento bee and purchased the newspaper a short 
time later 
he passed the newspaper to son ck mcclatchy who was editor 
and chairman of the company for 53 years until his death in 1936 
his daughter eleanor was the next president 
mcclatchy also was a member of the pulitzer prize board the 
newspaper advertising bureaus board of directors washington 
journalism center board of trustees and the american press 
institutes board of directors executive committee 
he is survived by two sons charles 30 of phoenix ariz 
kevin 26 of miami daughter adair 28 of san francisco two 
brothers james 68 of tiburon and ellery 64 of palm beach 
fla and his mother phebe of fesno 
he was divorced from his wife grace kennan whose father george 
kennan served as ambassador to the soviet union under president 
franklin roosevelt and was the architect of the postworld war ii 
containment policy against soviet expansionism 
funeral arrangements were not immediately announced 
