<TEXT>
eleven prominent scientists are urging the 
government not to rush into new production of tritium an important 
constituent of nuclear weapons until the soviet union has been 
sounded out about reductions in the nuclear stockpile 
tritium decays and must be replenished in nuclear weapons from 
time to time none has been produced in the united states since the 
aging reactors at the energy departments savannah river sc 
plant were shut down a year ago for safety upgrading 
officials have testified that at least one reactor must be 
restarted by the end of the year or the need for new tritium will 
become critical some members of congress have said failure to 
restart production would amount to unilateral nuclear disarmament 
the energy department plans to spend 75 billion to build two 
new tritiumproducing reactors that could be ready in 10 years 
in a statement dated sunday the 11 scientists said that once 
the options were studied it would be surprising not to find that 
tritium requirements to maintain a fully adequate stockpile of 
weapons could be met for about five years without additional 
production 
it should not take as long as five years however to determine 
whether the start and other armsreduction negotiations are likely 
to produce cuts sufficient to permit continued suspension of 
tritium production the scientists said 
their statement was organized by the nuclear control institute 
which has advocated a similar position the signers included two 
nobel prize winners and three former staff members of the los 
alamos national laboratory the principal nuclear weapons research 
and development installation 
a spokesman for the energy department did not immediately return 
a telephone call seeking comment 
the fusion of atoms of tritium which is hydrogen containing two 
neutrons instead of none is the driving force of thermonuclear 
weapons other weapons use the neutron burst from the fusion of 
small amounts of tritium to accelerate or boost the fission 
reactions of plutonium reducing the amount of plutonium required 
for the same explosive yield 
weapons are loaded with a surplus of tritium and reloaded when 
all the surplus is gone the reloading cycle is a secret and 
presumably varies from weapon to weapon the scientists noted 
published reports that the reloading cycle is four to six years for 
current weapons and 10 years for new submarinelaunched missiles 
the scientists advocated more frequent reloading with a smaller 
surplus and the use of tritium from warheads withdrawn under treaty 
terms or simply retired 
some may already have been taken into account and some may 
not provide much relief but certainly these and any other similar 
examples should be exploited before it is concluded that there is 
any imminent crisis the group said 
the 11 scientists are hans bethe retired professor of physics 
at cornell university freeman dyson professor of physics at the 
institute for advanced study in princeton nj herman feshbach 
retired professor of physics at massachusetts institute of 
technology val fitch professor of physics at princeton 
university marvin goldberger director of the institute for 
advanced study kurt gottfried professor of physics at cornell 
milton hoenig scientific director of the nuclear control 
institute franklin long retired professor of chemistry at 
cornell j carson mark consultant george rathjens professor of 
political science at mit and victor weisskopf retired professor of 
physics at mit 
bethe and fitch hold the nobel prize in physics and bethe mark 
and weisskopf formerly worked at los alamos all 11 have advised or 
worked in federal government agencies 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

