a 42 million drilling platform that 
capsized in heavy seas off south carolina 10 days ago drifted more 
than 280 miles to the northeast before finally sinking off north 
carolina officials said monday 
the 27500ton structure sank shortly before 1 am sunday about 
62 miles east of cape lookout nc coast guard chief warrant 
officer greg johnson said 
the platform was being towed from puerto rico to gloucester 
mass for a pipeline project when it capsized april 7 no one was 
aboard it the platform known as a jackup rig was used for 
exploratory drilling and other underwater projects 
authorities are not sure why it overturned but johnson said 
heavy seas contributed the coast guard is investigating 
after the platform capsized it slowly sank drifting northeast 
with the gulf stream johnson said a tug stayed with the rig to 
make sure no ships ran into it he said 
an estimated 500 gallons of oil hydraulic oil and diesel fuel 
were aboard the platform but officials dont feel that presents a 
major environmental threat because the platform sank well off the 
coast in water 1 miles deep johnson said 
the platform owned by maitland brothers inc of littlestown 
pa was built in 1978 by bethleham steel for 42 million said 
company spokesman edward mccormick 
