<TEXT>
president julio m sanguinetti said 
monday the question of amnesty for human rights abuses under 
military rule has been settled by voter approval of the amnesty law 
his government passed in 1986 
with 7037 of 7072 districts reporting in sundays referendum 
the vote was 1013554 for amnesty or 5262 percent and 771942 
4008 percent who wanted the law discarded 
sanguinetti a 52yearold lawyer told reporters monday now 
the discussion has ended 
when asked whether his government would consider a compromise 
with opponents of amnesty since they got nearly 41 percent of the 
vote he replied 
they were the ones who chose this way they were the ones who 
submitted the law to a majority vote national peace is to 
accept the verdict of the ballot box 
blank or invalid ballots and others classed as questionable 
that may or may not be counted totaled 140703 or 73 percent of 
the votes cast about 85 percent of eligible voters participated 
the amnesty law forbids prosecution of about 180 soldiers and 
police accused of torture murder and other crimes in 197385 when 
the military ruled uruguay and conducted what it called a war on 
leftist subversion 
it was passed by the new civilian government in december 1986 
after officers made clear they would not answer charges in the 
courts 
three military uprisings have occurred in neighboring argentina 
during the past two years because of the same issue argentina 
returned to civilian government in 1983 after nearly eight years of 
military rule and has tried many officers including former junta 
members 
uruguayans voted on amnesty because the national commission for 
a referendum gathered 634000 petition signatures during 1987 more 
than the required 25 percent of registered voters 
sanguinetti said his goal was to consolidate democracy in this 
nation of 3 million people which was an example of representative 
government to latin america before 1973 and in this case peace 
is justice 
he told the news conference amnesty does not excuse or justify 
military abuses which included the executions of about 150 
uruguayans arrests and disappearances of 200 more and the torture 
of several thousand 
it must be remembered he said that military intervention 
