<TEXT>
the agreement provided that wright would receive 325 nearly 
55 percent of the 595 list price on all retail sales of the 
book moore would receive 270 from which he would pay all 
printing and marketing expenses such royalty payments are 
unheard of in the publishing industry in fact wrights previous 
royalty contracts with three major publishers provided for standard 
industry royalties ranging from 10 percent to 15 percent depending 
upon sales morton janklow an expert on the publishing industry 
testified that no rational publisher would agree to a 55 percent 
royalty on list price because it could not make a profit janklow 
also testified that in his opinion as literary agent for nancy 
reagan sen daniel p moynihan helmut schmidt sidney sheldon and 
danielle steele wrights book was not commercially publishable 
although the agreement also provided that madison publishing 
would publish and market the book in fact wright and his staff 
provided many of the ordinary services of a publisher and made the 
most significant contribution to marketing efforts 
in this instance moore designed the layout and printed the 
cover of the book he hired others to typeset and print the book 
itself all other aspects of book production were performed by 
wright or his staff moore also sent out 300 to 500 letters 
soliciting orders for the book and employed 12 to 15 people for 
four hours a day during one week to make telephone solicitations 
from voter registration lists moore arranged an autograph party 
one or two newspaper advertisements and an appearance by wright on 
the larry king show moores marketing efforts resulted in precious 
few sales to average citizens in fact moore testified that he 
never intended to sell the book to bookstores where average people 
could buy them because bookstores would only purchase at the 
discount price of 300 per copy that doesnt leave you much 
room 
the real focus of the marketing effort for reflections of a 
public man was on bulk sales to trade associations and other 
groups almost 98 percent of all sales of reflections of a public 
man were bulk sales of 15 or more books in some instances 
wrights staff informed various groups wright spoke to that because 
he had already reached the maximum limit on outside earned income 
for that year he would not be able to keep an honoraium offered to 
him the staff then recommended that instead of paying wright an 
honorarium the organization could purchase books for the same 
amount 
for example wright gave a lecture in october 1984 at southwest 
texas state university the university paid wright an honorarium of 
3000 in addition to his expenses but was subsequently informed 
by wrights staff that he would be unable to accept the honorarium 
wrights staff suggested that the university purchase 504 books for 
3000 in lieu of the honorarium the university purchased the 
books and distributed most of them to students in its political 
science department wright endorsed the 3000 check over to 
madison publishing company despite the change in the nature of the 
transaction the universitys records plainly list the 3000 
expenditure as an honorarium for wrights appearance instead of 
passing up 3000 or donating it to charity wright thus received a 
1650 royalty for his lecture at the university 
wright also spoke at a satellite broadcasting and communications 
association sbca trade show in september 1985 just several 
weeks after sbca had purchased 1680 copies of reflections of a 
public man for 10000 sbca testified that although it 
historically has paid honoraria and expenses to congressmen for 
their appearances in this case sbcas legal counsel who arranged 
for wright to speak at the trade show suggested that sbca purchase 
the books instead thus wright received a 5500 royalty for 
his appearance before the sbca 
not all bulk sales were in lieu of honoraria for example 
carlos moore arranged a sale of 2000 books to the teamsters for 
12200 paid out of the drive political fund the books were 
distributed to teamster members wright had not spoken at any 
teamster event 
in addition s gene payte a fort worth real estate developer 
testified that he wanted to give wright a 5000 gift and in fact 
had given a 5000 check to betty wright wright subsequently 
informed him that he could not accept the gift and returned the 
check to payte payte continued to search for a way to give cash to 
wright and shortly after receiving the first check back from 
wright wrote a second 5000 check this time to madison systems 
for revision and distribution of wrights books payte 
testified that he expected to receive 1000 copies of the revised 
edition of the book and in fact he made a second payment of 
1000 when he realized that 5000 would not buy 1000 copies of 
the 595 book however the book was never revised payte 
testified he received approximately 300 to 500 copies of the old 
book instead no further accounting was made 
