<TEXT>
in 1981 mallightco loaned the wrights an additional 37000 
over the period 1981 through 1983 the wrights and the mallicks 
made regular payments on their loans from the proceeds of their 
other investments however beginning in 1984 the wrights made 
little progress in reducing the outstanding principal balance and 
in fact were not meeting their interest payments the debt 
continued to accrue interest mallightco never demanded payment 
from the wrights or took any steps to collect the debt 
mallightco distributed several dividends to its shareholders in 
1986 and 1987 despite the wrights failure to make significant 
payments on their loans the company distributed 59000 in cash to 
the wrights as dividends while the mallicks also received 
dividends during this period all dividends to the mallicks were 
paid in the form of credits against their outstanding debts to the 
company until their loans were completely repaid in 1987 
on june 9 1988 the wrights through the james c wright jr 
blind trust formed in october 1987 sold their mallightco shares 
back to the company for 350000 the alleged market value of the 
shares at the time of sale the price consisted of 230000 cash 
and a 120000 unsecured fiveyear 10 percent interestbearing 
note subordinate to all present and future debt of mallightco the 
wrights paid back most of their outstanding loan balance then 
80000 from the cash received from the sale approximately 
12700 in accured interest was forgiven in the transaction between 
mallightco and the blind trust 
it appears that the wrights received greater benefit from their 
interest in mallightco than did the mallicks since the wrights had 
the use of a substantial amount of cash provided by the mallicks 
however although no effort was made to collect the wrights loans 
from mallightco those loans did accrue interest at the rate of 
approximately 10 percent per year and were ultimately paid back 
almost entirely although 12700 in interest was not paid back 
that transaction occurred between mallick and the trustee of 
wrights blind trust special outside counsel assumes that wright 
was unaware of this gift to his blind trust and will rectify the 
account with mallick when the gift is made known to him thus 
wright ultimately paid for the use of the money he borrowed and has 
apparently not violated any law or ethical standard with respect to 
his mallightco investment 
on the other hand we believe that wright violated house rules 
with respect to his indirect receipt of and failure to report 
additional gifts from the mallicks bestowed in the form of salary 
paid to betty wright by mallightco free housing to the wrights in 
fort worth from 1979 through march 1988 and the use of a 1979 
cadillac seville in washington dc from 1983 until approximately 
february 1989 
betty wright began working for mallick in 1979 as a parttime 
consultant for mallick properties inc which hired mrs wright to 
help mallick expand his real estate ventures into areas of texas 
beyond fort worth mrs wright earned 18000 per year for her 
parttime work on a brochure entitled the mallick community 
concept for market studies of austin and san antonio texas and 
for her access to officials and other key people in the austin and 
san antonio areas although it is impossible to determine how much 
time mrs wright devoted to her employment with mallick properties 
inc it does appear that she did identifiable work on projects 
arguably within her expertise which may have been worth 18000 a 
year to the company 
on january 1 1981 mrs wright went on the payroll of 
mallightco inc at a salary of 1500 per month according to 
mallick mrs wright was hired as a consultant to seek out new 
investment opportunities for mallightco however mrs wright 
formerly on the staff of the subcommittee on investigations and 
oversight of the house public works committee had no education or 
prior experience in investment analysis or financial counseling 
she performed few if any services to mallightco which has no 
record of any work product she created 
furthermore although mallick testified that mrs wright 
assisted him and advised him he could not articulate what 
valuable services she performed he testified to research she did 
on several investment opportunities during the four years she was 
paid by mallightco but could not produce any research reports or 
even point to one investment mrs wright researched which was 
ultimately made by the company 
moreover although mallick was the one responsible for making 
investment decisions and both he and his assistant pamela smith 
performed services of value for mallightco neither mallick nor 
smith received a salary from mallightco in fact mrs wrights 
salary was mallightcos greatest expense the company frequently 
had to borrow money from the mallick company or other mallick 
entities in order to pay mrs wrights salary ultimately 
mallightco could not continue the expense mrs wrights salary was 
suspended as of december 31 1984 thus from 1981 through 1984 
mrs wrights salary was a gift from mallick 
