<TEXT>
nearly 2000 students swarmed into central 
beijings tiananmen square by bicycle and on foot before dawn 
tuesday and cheered demands that the communist partys ruling 
politburo resign 
more than 1500 students in shanghai also took to the streets to 
express grief over the death saturday of former communist party 
chief hu yaobang and to demand more democracy 
students marched in both cities monday they put up posters on 
campus mourning hu a liberal reformist and expressing vague 
dissatisfaction with the government 
a poster at beijing university attacked senior leader deng 
xiaoping for the first time although not by name it blamed the 
84yearold deng for hus removal in 1987 
the marches were the largest since the 198687 prodemocracy 
demonstrations that led to hus forced resignation conservatives 
accused hu of being too liberal and failing to halt student 
demonstrations 
tuesdays demonstrations brought the revived student movement 
closer to a new political stage 
beijing students cheered when one speaker climbed on a monument 
to chinas revolutionary heroes and demanded that the 22member 
politburo resign 
they cheered a demand that party leaders reassess hus place in 
history it could not be determined how many demonstrators joined 
in formulating the demands 
most students dispersed after reaching tiananmen but about 200 
staged a sitin before the great hall of the people the national 
seat of government next to the square 
they presented six demands to the national peoples congress or 
parliament including reassessment of hus role opposition to 
antiliberal political campaigns and disclosure of leaders 
incomes they demanded freedom of speech and press higher pay for 
intellectuals and lifting restrictions on street marches 
the six demands did not include one for the politburos 
resignation 
an unidentified official received the demands but said they were 
major matters that needed to be studied at length 
the students sang the national anthem and the socialist 
internationale chanted long live democracy and oppose 
dictatorship and asked other students back on the campus to join 
them 
the fourhour march from campuses in northern beijing to 
tiananmen had the atmosphere of a recreational outing 
students joked and laughed and many said they didnt know what 
they would do once they reached tiananmen 
were going to honor the memory of hu yaobang one said 
we dont have any political goals 
several said the march began spontaneously shortly after 
midnight at beijing university which is chinas leading university 
and has a history of political activism students from other 
schools joined the procession along with some bystanders 
several students carrying a white sheet with the words chinas 
spirit led the march 
a few police stationed around the square made no attempt to 
interfere 
more than 600 students from beijings political science and law 
college marched to tiananmen on monday and placed two funeral 
wreaths at the monument 
in shanghai thousands of students from fudan university 
participated in marches that began sunday 
jason hurpado of portland ore an english teacher at fudan 
said students sang revolutionary songs during the first march 
substituting hus name for that of revolutionary leader mao 
tsetung 
this weeks marches reflected not only grief at hus death but 
also the volatility among students unhappy with living conditions 
and bleak career prospects 
the officially supervised student union at beijing university 
in an apparent attempt to channel the students emotions set up a 
temporary memorial hall honoring hu the communist party has said 
an official memorial service will be held in the great hall of the 
people but no date has been set 
hu was eulogized by the party as a statesman and proletarian 
revolutionary 
</TEXT>
