<TEXT>
in early 1986 the federal home loan bank board the bank 
board perceiving worsening conditions in the southwests 
economy and thrift industry began a massive examination of almost 
all the savings and loan associations in district 9 which included 
associations in texas new mexico louisiana arkansas and 
mississippi as a result the bank board discovered that many 
associations especially those in texas where state regulations 
were especially permissive were built on risky investments 
uncollectible loans and fraudulent appraisals while the real 
estate market was booming these associations appeared to be doing 
well however when the bottom dropped out of the texas real estate 
market the bank boards examinations showed that much of the 
profit had been imaginary 
the burgeoning number of savings and loan failures in texas and 
elsewhere placed enormous strains on the fslic fund which insures 
deposits in federal and statechartered savings and loan 
associations under federal law when fslic places an insolvent 
federallyinsured savings association into a receivership it must 
pay off the insured depositors almost immediately therefore each 
closure requires fslic to make an immediate cash outlay 
approximately equal to the insolvent associations deposits as 
fslics reserves dwindled it lost the financial ability to close 
even the most insolvent associations in late 1986 approximately 
250 associations required fslic assistance of these fslic 
considered 130 associations with stated assets of 476 billion 
to be severely troubled 
in response to this crisis in may 1986 a bill was introduced in 
the house of representatives which provided among other items 15 
billion in new funds for fslic without the use of general revenues 
the bill was referred to the house committee on banking finance 
and urban affairs which passed the bill by a vote of 47 to 1 
without significant amendment the bill was placed on the 
suspension calendar and was scheduled for consideration by the full 
house on monday september 29 1986 the suspension calendar is 
reserved for bills engendering little controversy however wright 
removed it from the calendar prior to its consideration the bill 
was rescheduled on october 6 1986 and on october 7 1986 it passed 
the house under suspension of the rules however because the 
senates version of the bill contained controversial provisions 
insufficient time remained to resolve the differences before 
congress adjourned on october 18 1986 
on january 6 1987 substantially the same bill was reintroduced 
in the new congress the banking committee held hearings later in 
january as members began increasingly to pass along complaints 
about regulators arbitrary actions in closing down savings and 
loan associations for the first time forbearance provisions 
ie provisions restricting fslics ability to close associations 
were discussed as part of the bill wright supported these 
forbearance provisions as well as a reduction in the 
recapitalization amount to 5 billion the bank board believed the 
forbearance provisions and the reduced recapitalization amount 
would severely hamper its ability to deal with the crisis although 
wright later supported 15 billion the house passed the 
recapitalization bill at the 5 billion level the amount was 
raised to 108 billion in conference and the forbearance 
provisions were weakened the bill was signed into law in august 
1987 
during this 19861987 period wright intervened with the bank 
board on behalf of four texas businessmen who were deeply embroiled 
in the savings and loan crisis one of these businessmen craig 
hall met with wright on september 2 1986 and informed him that 
the bank board was out of control and taking action against him 
which would have serious repercussions in the dallas and texas 
communities 
hall is a dallasbased real estate syndicator and one of the 
largest owners of real estate in texas once hall determined that 
the worsening texas economy threatened his ability to remain 
current on loans held by numerous savings and loan associations he 
sought assistance from the bank board and district banks in 
restructuring his debts held by fsliccontrolled savings and loans 
although the bank board was not adverse to the concept of a 
global restructuring it believed it could not legally assume the 
role of negotiator for those associations involved in the hall 
restructuring which were already under fslic control hall was 
required to negotiate individual agreements with the special 
representatives of each fsliccontrolled association 
hall was able to reach agreement with all but one 
fsliccontrolled association the westwood savings and loan of los 
angeles which held approximately 200 million in hall loans 
westwoods bank boardappointed special representative scott 
schultz and its outside counsel refused to accept conditions to 
the restructuring which were adverse to westwoods interests and 
decided to foreclose on halls properties and allow him to go 
bankrupt rather than accept his restructuring plan 
at the onset of foreclosure proceedings the bank board and 
district banks ceased communication with hall hall told wright in 
their september 2 1986 meeting that he had received no response to 
his efforts to reestablish communication with the bank board and 
district banks soon after meeting with hall wright called a 
meeting in his office with several texas congressmen and 
representatives of the bank board including its chairman edwin 
gray although hall may have been mentioned the meeting was 
generally devoted to passing along reports that bank board 
regulators were mistreating texas savings and loans 
wright called gray shortly after the meeting to complain about 
westwoods special representative scott schultz whom wright said 
was not as flexible or understanding as he might be wright asked 
if there was not anything gray could do about that situation 
wright never discussed the merits of the bank boards position and 
he rebuffed the bank boards offer to explain its position in the 
hall matter 
gray decided to further investigate the hall matter on friday 
september 26 1986 bank board chief of staff shannon fairbanks 
went to a meeting with hall and his california savings and loan 
creditors on that day hall learned that because of wrights 
interest in halls situation wright had placed a hold on the 
fslic recapitalization bill which had been scheduled for 
consideration by the house on the following monday 
gray and fairbanks thus determined that if they were to obtain a 
recapitalization bill they would have to facilitate a 
restructuring of halls loans on september 29 1986 gray replaced 
scott schultz with another special representative who was 
instructed to disregard outside couunsels legal advice and 
determine if there was any way to build a responsible economic case 
in support of renegotiating halls loans following grays removal 
of schultz and grays later assurances to wright that the bank 
board would not treat texas savings and loans unfairly the bill 
was returned to the house calendar it was passed by the full house 
under a suspension of the rules on october 7 1986 
</TEXT>
