<TEXT>
wright did not merely urge prompt consideration of or 
express judgment on the hall matter as specifically permitted 
in the select committee on ethics advisory opinion no 1 he 
removed the recapitalization bill from house consideration in order 
to pressure the bank board into changing its resolution of the hall 
matter regardless of the merits of the bank boards position such 
pressure is a violation of house rule xliii clause 1 as 
interpreted by advisory opinion no 1 
on october 6 1986 wright met with j scott mann iii an 
austin texas savings and loan operator who complained that the 
bank board was discriminating against texas savings and loans 
associations and that a recapitalized fslic would close large 
numbers of texas institutions mann also set forth his complaints 
in a letter of october 7 1986 which wright forwarded to gray 
asking that he check on the situations described gray investigated 
manns charges and reported to wright that manns creditbanc 
savings had committed serious regulatory violations and was in a 
precarious financial condition wright took no further action thus 
wrights request that gray check on manns charges is within the 
guidelines of advisory opinion no 1 which expressly provides that 
it is appropriate for a member to request information or a status 
report 
in early november 1986 wright telephoned gray regarding 
wrights friend thomas m gaubert of independent american 
savings association a texaschartered association with its main 
office in irving texas gaubert was also a contributor to the 
democratic party and treasurer of the democratic congressional 
campaign committee 
in january 1986 gaubert had been permanently removed from 
independent american and prohibited from operating any 
fslicinsured association gaubert had been involved in 
questionable transactions at an iowa savings and loan as well as 
regulatory violations and unsafe or unsound practices at 
independent american as of november 30 1986 independent american 
had a negative net worth of 454 million although gaubert entered 
into a written agreement removing him from the industry he later 
argued that he had been misled and treated unfairly and therefore 
that the agreement was invalid 
wright asked gray to meet with gaubert personally in order to 
get gauberts side of the story gray protested that bank board 
rules prohibit the chairman from meeting with parties to actions 
before the board despite grays protests wright insisted that 
gray meet with gaubert gray did so as an accommodation to wright 
following his meeting with gaubert gray made the unprecedented 
decision in january or february 1987 to appoint an independent 
counsel selected by counsel for gaubert to determine whether the 
bank board had in fact wrongfully removed gaubert from independent 
american gray testified that but for his perception of wrights 
influence on the recapitalization bill he would not have appointed 
independent counsel independent counsel ultimately determined that 
the bank board had not violated any statutes or regulations in its 
treatment of gaubert although it did note some instances of 
improper or unfair behavior none of which justified gauberts 
claim that he was removed improperly 
nonetheless despite the significant concessions made by gray 
at a meeting with officials of the bank board and fhlbdallas on 
february 10 1987 in wrights office wright made it plain that he 
viewed the outcome of the gaubert matter to have been extremely 
unsatisfactory the clear inference is that wright was not simply 
seeking impartial consideration of gauberts claim but a change in 
the bank boards regulatory response to gaubert such use of 
wrights influence is a violation of house rule xliii clause 1 as 
interpreted by advisory opinion no 1 
in december 1986 congressman tony coelho called wrights aide 
john mack and requested wrights assistance on behalf of don r 
dixon of vernon savings and loan in dallas and vernon texas 
coelho informed mack that the fslic was going to shut down vernon 
that day he asked that wright attempt to get dixon a grace period 
as dixon said he had a willing buyer 
mack testified that following his conversation with coelho he 
told wright of dixons problem wright telephoned gray and asked 
him whether vernon was being closed down gray responded that 
closing an institution requires a bank board meeting and he had not 
authorized any such meeting wright asked gray to find out if 
anything was happening and to call john mack with the information 
gray later informed mack that vernon was not being shut down 
but the fhlbdallas supervisory agents were going to seek a 
consent to merger agreement from vernons directors at the end 
of december 1986 gray explained that such an agreement would not 
affect the associations ability to find an investor and that mack 
should let the bank board know if an investor were found 
ultimately no investor was found and vernon was placed in 
receivership in march 1987 
in this instance since wright merely asked for information from 
the bank board no violation occurred 
in november 1986 wright again called gray to express his 
concern about the way texas institutions were being treated by the 
bank board he brought up the subject of h joe selby the director 
of regulatory affairs at the fhlbdallas and formerly the acting 
comptroller of the currency who had the reputation of being a 
tough regulator and who had been brought into the savings and loan 
crisis by gray to implement the bank boards supervisory and 
regulatory response because of his hardline posture selby was 
feared and distrusted by many in the thirft industry 
wright told gray he understood from unnamed sources that selby 
was a homosexual who was sending all of fhlbdallas work to a 
ring of homosexual lawyers in texas wright asked gray if there 
was anything gray could do to get rid of selby gray refused 
wrights request and defended selby as a highly competent regulator 
doing the tough job expected of him 
although unsuccessful wrights attempt to destroy selbys 
career based upon such an accusation violates house rule xliii 
clause 1 because it does not reflect creditably on the house 
similarly when in late 1987 or early 1988 wrights aide phil 
duncan called carl hoyle the bank boards director of 
congressional affairs and said he wanted william black fired from 
the staff of the fhlbsan francisco such a request indirectly from 
wright is also a violation of house rule xliii clause 1 
thus as discussed in full in section iii f of this report 
wright committed four violations of house rule xliii clause 1 as 
interpreted by advisory opinion no 1 
