<TEXT>
after eight years of sometimes 
bitter controversy bavarian leaders are planning a youth center in 
dachau to help teach younger generations of the nazi horrors that 
occurred in its notorious concentration camp 
but deep philosophical differences remain over just how the 
center will pass on its bitter lessons 
politicians here in highly conservative bavaria want the youth 
center to be under governmental control they envision it as a 
youth hostel that would combine instruction about the nazis with a 
chance to learn about the modernday city of dachau 
on the other side an association that has members in several 
countries argues that the leadership of the center should reflect 
more diverse views and be more international in scope 
the association for a dachau international youth meeting center 
says the guest house should serve almost exclusively as a forum to 
analyze the nazi past and its implications today 
juergen zarusky a leader of the association said he sees 
dangers in government control 
that means everything must be under government protection so 
that the past will be presented as a formal history lesson 
zarusky said in an interview both the personal impact and the 
search for meaning for today wont be presented as strongly 
zarusky a 30yearold doctoral candidate in modern history 
whos lived in dachau for three years said his group feels 
unfairly excluded from the project because local conservatives fear 
this could go in a leftist direction 
the concentration camp site including a museum and memorials to 
the dead already attracts about a million visitors a year 
twothirds of them foreigners the site also contains watch towers 
barbed wire fences a reconstructed barracks and the crematorium 
where the dead were once burned 
dachau which is about five miles north of munich was the first 
of a string of nazi concentration camps that became centers mainly 
for the extermination of jews mostly in gas chambers in world war 
ii 
official nazi records say that 206000 prisoners were kept at 
dachau although the actual number is believed to be much higher 
nazi records say that nearly 32000 prisoners died there but 
thousands of other deaths were not registered 
the nazis set up the concentration camp at dachau two months 
after seizing power jan 30 1933 its prisoners included jews 
communists social democrats clergymen and other opponents of the 
nazi regime 
bavarian officials opened the camp as a memorial in 1965 after 
agreeing to cooperate with the brusselsbased international dachau 
committee in supervising the site the committee made up of former 
dachau prisoners has representatives on the board of trustees of 
the association that wants an international youth center 
the association was formed in 1984 after three years of efforts 
by a local committee to establish a place where young people could 
meet and spend the night 
the plans ran into vehement opposition from the conservative 
christian social union officials at dachaus city hall they 
repeatedly have maintained that such a center would unfairly a 
create an extra burden on a city already saddled with a 
notorious past 
in 1987 members of the state parliament in munich filed several 
motions seeking to take the matter out of local hands as a way to 
find a solution 
as a result the bavarian education ministry this past september 
approved a plan for creating the youth center with sleeping 
accommodations for about 100 people as well as meeting rooms for 
both west germans and foreigners 
the youth guest house should contribute to enabling and 
promoting a discussion of the past that is linked to the spirit of 
democratic responsibility the education ministry said 
in its proposal for dachau however the education ministry 
called for the exclusion of events focusing on daytoday 
politics 
the ministrys manfred heger who is handling the project said 
the guest house is supposed to be multifunctional 
it isnt supposed to be set up exclusively for instruction 
about the camp memorial the concentration camp site nazism and 
fascism 
the association for a dachau international youth meeting center 
has rejected the government plan and continues to push for its own 
ideas including a greater reliance on former prisoners to narrate 
their horrifying experiences 
gabi hendl another leading member of the association brushes 
aside objections that the center could damage the citys reputation 
this youth meeting center is a chance for dachau and the 
people who live in the city to hear what young people from other 
countries are thinking said the 24yearold ms hendl a member 
of the leftistleaning social democratic party 
another member of the association is nikolaus lehner 65 a jew 
who survived dachau 
we arent politicizing he said were discussing 
history 
</TEXT>
