<TEXT>
its called the snow train or the moose meat 
special depending on the time of year and the interests of its 
passengers and for tourists its a way to pierce the wilds of 
canada without severe damage to the household budget first built 
to haul iron ore and timber out of the hinterland north of sault 
ste marie the algoma central railway was later discovered by 
hunters artists and sightseers 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the train is highballing 
through an awesome crack in the earths surface on a scenic 
journey to nowhere and back 
inside the nofrills passenger cars steam heat and the morning 
sun fog the wide windows 
a bored kid punches his sister in the arm she wails 
their grandmother is preoccupied with the vista outside the 
window pristine soft snow and black rock snow so deep it reaches 
the roofs of fishing cabins 
in the dining car a young couple from detroit asks if they can 
get american bacon instead of canadian bacon with their eggs three 
happygolucky guys lurch down the aisle without spilling a drop 
from their open cans of beer 
all had crossed the us border at sault ste marie and bought a 
35 ticket for an eighthour roundtrip train ride through the 
canadian wilderness to eaton 120 miles to the north 
ninety years ago the algoma central railway first pierced the 
canadian hinterland it was built to bring iron ore out of wawa and 
timber out of hearst then it was discovered by artists sportsmen 
and tourists who know it by such names as the snow train or the 
moose meat special depending on the time of year business is 
brisk in the snowbound winter gets even better during the spring 
and summer 
today lucy dassance was riding the rail with her daughters 
family the seven of them among the hundreds of americans who take 
algoma centrals weekend tour each year 
a local makes regular stops along the way during the week but 
on the weekend sightseeing run there are no stops no depots just 
ride to the end of the line get up turn your seats around and 
ride back 
my husband didnt come mrs dassance says he said he had 
enough snow back in michigan 
outside a cold wind rips through agawa canyon tearing at the 
rock walls with ice crystals further eroding this wild open cut 
in the earths skin 
the agawa canyon has been molded by erosion and sculpted by 
glacier up close it is a narrow cleft in the dark gray rock 
through which a river tumbles and the railroad runs giant 
pressures thrust up granite mountains so long ago the range has 
eroded to its jutting broken spine volcanic fissures shot up 
veins rich with minerals gold iron phosphate silica sand 
it takes a satellite to show the gorges true nature a 90mile 
northsouth crack in the planet says ed frey a staff geologist 
for ontarios ministry of northern development and mines the 
rail line follows a natural weakness in the earths crust its a 
major fault 
agawa means sheltered place to don stones people the 
ojibwa from michipicoten harbour near the rails midpoint stone 
guides american hunters and tells black bear legends handed down 
from his father and grandfather 
stones stories also include a topical account of the 1850 
treaty his people signed with the crown giving away land that 30 
years later was granted to the railroads to open up ontario 
the mining and timbering produced small towns along the track 
hawk junction batchawana searchmont but so much of the 
territory remains a wilderness that game hunters ride in by rail 
shoot their quarry and then flag down the train for the ride back 
in october moose season the algoma central railway adds cars 
to carry the quarry they call it the moose meat special but moose 
isnt the only meat on board 
ive seen bear ride the train too stone says 
you could get there by road in many places but that loses the 
romanticism he says 
there was no road beyond batchawana when the algoma line 
attracted its first train tourists a band of rebel canadian 
artists called the group of seven 
in 1918 some of these radical artists hopped a caboose in sault 
ste marie to ride into the wild algoma they shunted from siding 
to siding sketching the strong land with wild picasso skies on the 
inside covers of their cigarbox palettes 
the art world laughed but the seven prevailed they would become 
some of canadas most famous artists 
