<TEXT>
for the first time in nearly 20 years chileans 
will elect a president this year to replace an ironfisted military 
leader but it could be too early for rejoicing this is another in 
a series of periodic reports by the associated press on the 
economic social and political turbulence that has turned south 
america into a continent in crisis 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
lame ducks though they may be chiles 
military leaders already are casting an ominous shadow over the 
civilian government that will take office next year 
they have made it unabashedly clear that while they will step 
aside they wont step out and will seize power again if they think 
it is necessary 
and therein lies a major difficulty for the civilian who wins 
the presidential election dec 14 and takes over march 11 from gen 
augusto pinochet the ironfisted president since 1973 
the military government will bequeath a growing and stable 
economy to the civilians but they also will leave deep and 
potentially explosive social imbalances 
millions of chileans are still poor as they were when pinochet 
led the military into the civilian disarray of september 1973 and 
overthrew president salvador allende the marxist who professed to 
want to help the poor 
recent opinion polls indicate that while chileans have a 
relatively robust economy low salaries and unemployment are high 
on their list of priorities for the civilian government 
as politicians prepare for the election pinochet and other 
military leaders make it clear they do not plan a complete retreat 
from the political scene 
pinochet recently said military leaders have the obligation to 
ensure that the future civilian president is an authentic 
democratic man 
and the military is on record that it wont hesitate to 
intervene again 
if the institutional order is broken the armed forces have 
the duty to restore it using compulsion and all the necessary 
means gen alejandro medina head of a center of strategic 
studies said in a recent lecture to noncommissioned officers 
civilian politicians complain that will place the armed forces 
in the role of armed guardians of the civilian government 
a constitution drawn up by the military government in 1980 gives 
the armed forces the means for such a role it allows pinochet who 
still commands the army and the commanders of the navy air force 
and national police to keep their posts until 1998 
pinochet who is constitutionally prohibited from seeking 
reelection in december has already said he will remain as army 
commander after the election 
that is tantamount to creating an armed state within an 
unarmed democratic state said genero arriagada vice president 
of the centrist christian democratic party the largest in the 
opposition 
the constitution also established a militarydominated national 
council which may represent its views to the civilian 
government on key matters 
more complicated for the future leaders may be the problem of 
human rights violations during 16 years of military rule 
opposition leaders say that should they win the election they 
will investigate the abuses and try those found responsible 
the military leaders have made it clear however they it will 
not permit reprisals for what they see as actions that were part of 
a war 
in the military years thousands of leftists were arrested many 
were sent into exile and hundreds were killed local and foreign 
human rights groups have documented more than 700 cases of 
dissidents who disappeared after being arrested by security forces 
a recent opinion poll taken by the center for public studies an 
independent research institute however indicates that chileans 
are more interested in their personal economic situations than in 
the political complexities of the process to restore civilian rule 
or in the military threats to take power again 
in a nationwide poll taken by the center in march and april 46 
percent of the respondents mentioned low salaries and inefficient 
public health services as the two top items on a civilian 
governments agenda 
