<TEXT>
kings county hospital is the parris island of 
american medicine a sometimes hellish boot camp that tuns out 
seasoned professionals 
it has 140 internists in training more than any other us 
institution and some of the citys poorest and sickest people 
recruiting a few good men and women however has been getting 
harder and harder 
five years ago 90 percent of the hospitals medicine residents 
staff doctors in training were graduates of american medical 
schools today less than half are even in the worst years kings 
county could count on getting 20 to 25 graduates of the medical 
school of the state university of new york with which it is 
affiliated last year not a single suny graduate applied and only 
three of 60 firstyear residents are from american schools 
there are a many reasons why young doctors might shun a hospital 
like kings county but heres the most obvious half the patients 
in the internal medicine service have aids that may have been 
the straw that broke the camels back says dr richard schwartz 
the medical schools provost 
with more than 8800 residents new york city hospitals train 
almost 10 percent of the nations physicians three times more 
than any other city but at a time when the hospitals need more 
residents than ever the quality and quantity of applicants is 
declining leading teaching hospitals cant attract their top 
recruits and others have scrambled to fill their residency slots 
with graduates of foreign medical schools 
in recent years fewer us medical students have gone into less 
lucrative primary care specialities like internal medicine and 
pediatrics new york seems to be having more trouble attracting 
such residents than other cities and one thing that sets it apart 
from them is aids it has a fourth of the nations cases and in 
two years as many as 10000 of its 25000 general hospital beds 
could be filled by aids patients 
although the chances of doctors catching acquired immune 
deficiency syndrome from their patients are low a survey at new 
york and san francisco hospitals found that fear of aids 
preoccupied doctors and gave them nightmares 
medical students can be so overwhelmed with aids patients you 
dont get the broad experience a resident wants says caroline 
reich of emory university chairmanelect of student 
representatives to the american association of medical colleges 
a residency is supposed to expose young physicians to a wide 
variety of illnesses and patients doctors worry that if too many 
of their patients have aids their exposure becomes too narrow and 
their diagnostic skills atrophy a residency is also supposed to be 
educational but aids patients are so sick that their care leaves 
little time for study or consultation with senior doctors 
donald wilson is chief of medicine at kings county hospital 
when he was making his hospital rounds as a resident 25 years ago 
he usually had to spend only five to 10 minutes with each patient 
a good proportion of them werent particularly sick he says 
now though one aids patient might require as much time and 
attention as six of the people i used to see wilson says it 
takes an enormous toll physicially and emotionally on our staff 
aids is the health care crisis of the decade but in much of the 
nation it remains an exotic curiosity most people who are 
looking to go into private practice dont think theyll be seeing 
many aids patients and dont feel they need an intensive exposure 
to aids during their residency says cindy osman of brown 
