<TEXT>
lockheed corp today delivered the last of 50 
c5b jumbo cargo planes to the air force completing a sevenyear 
69 billion contract that drew accusations of greed from congress 
the final c5b the biggest air cargo carrier in the free world 
took off after a ceremony made a salute lap around lockheed 
aeronautical systems co headquarters in suburban marietta and then 
headed for the air base at dover del 
the company has no plans for further production of the c5b 
said robert z christopher director of the c5 program lockheed 
aeronautical is a division of lockheed corp the calabasas 
califbased aeronautics giant 
the c5b is 248 feet long has a wing span of 223 feet and a 
65foot tshaped tail high as a sixstory building 
the jet an updated version of the c5a can carry almost any 
piece of the armys hardware two 50ton m1 tanks for example 
it has been used recently for such nonmilitary missions as 
carrying equipment and supplies to the site of the exxon valdez oil 
spill in alaska and aid to the victims of the earthquake in the 
soviet republic of armenia said air force spokesman capt tom 
dolney 
the huge contract has been a boon to the atlantaarea providing 
thousands of jobs and pumping millions of subcontracting dollars 
into 40 states 
todays ceremony marked a happy landing in the flight of the 
c5b project but it was a bumpy ride 
lockheed won the contract in 1982 beating out boeing and 
mcdonnell douglas the original pact was for 78 billion 
production of the planes predecessor the c5a was marred by 
revelations that the air force had purchased ineffective repair 
kits from lockheed that included 22994 nickelsized washers 
shortly before the first c5b was to be delivered in late 1985 
it was discovered that tens of thousands of nuts on the planes had 
to be replaced because the ones installed were the wrong kind 
the pentagon accused the company of inflating the c5b contract 
by as much as 500 million by withholding details of a proposed 
twotier wage system for its new employees by 1987 the price tag 
had been whittled down to 69 billion 
a review by the general accounting office congress 
investigative arm found that in late 1986 lockheed proposed to 
charge the government 21113 for an inchlong shim a metal wedge 
that was an excess part from c5b production and originally valued 
at 2209 
last month the air force said it had imposed flight 
restrictions on 20 c5bs because of a problem with the pylon the 
assembly that holds the jet engine to the wing 
lockheed has proposed to the air force that the plant maintain 
its c5b tooling company spokesman doug oliver said 
their decision will pretty much tell us what the future of the 
c5b is he said 
</TEXT>
