<DOCNO> AP890417-0275 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a federal appeals court on monday allowed 
the state of california to go to trial with claims that six major 
oil companies conspired to depress the price of oil they pumped 
from stateowned tidelands in long beach 
the suits in federal and state court claim losses to the state 
and the city of long beach totaling 789 million in 197177 and 
198085 damages tripled under antitrust law would exceed 23 
billion and could be increased further by 2500aday penalties 
sought under state unfaircompetition laws 
most of the claimed losses were to the state which uses 
tidelands oil money for school construction the city of long beach 
gets a small fraction of the oil money 
the 9th us circuit court of appeals voted 30 to reinstate the 
suits which had been dismissed by us district judge william gray 
of los angeles 
the suits accuse the six companies standard oil co of 
california texaco inc union oil mobil corp shell oil co and 
exxon corp of holding down the prices they paid for heavy crude 
oil while agreeing secretly to exchange oil among themselves at 
higher prices a seventh defendant atlantic richfield co settled 
in 1984 by paying 225 million 
still pending before the appellate court is an appeal by 
california and four other states from a ruling by gray dismissing a 
separate antitrust suit against the same seven oil companies which 
accuses them of conspiring to create a gasoline shortage and fix 
gasoline prices in the early 1970s 
in mondays ruling the court said the state and city had 
presented enough evidence to proceed to trial with claims that the 
oil companies conspired to keep artificially low the prices they 
paid to long beach for heavy crude oil 
royce schulz a lawyer for the city said retail prices for oil 
products in california were about the same as those elsewhere in 
the period an indication that the companies actions didnt help 
consumers 
refiners simply pocketed that profit he said 
the suits contend the companies agreed secretly in the early 
1960s at meetings involving all of them except exxon to keep the 
posted price for heavy crude below its real value while exchanging 
different grades of oil among themselves at higher rates 
lawyers for long beach said the elaborate exchange procedure 
unique to california was disclosed by a state auditor in 1973 but 
was being used as late as 1984 
types of oil were used as a currency a medium of exchange 
and a new value system reserved to the majors oil companies and 
kept secret from the state and the city schulz said in a 
background paper on the case 
gary halling another partner in schulzs firm said the secrecy 
of the exchange system let the oil companies evade a provision of 
their contract with long beach that required them to pay the city 
the highest price they paid any other seller of oil 
but david destino a lawyer for exxon said the exchange system 
simply allowed oil companies to move their product to market while 
guaranteeing that they would get equal value when trading the same 
grade of oil from different sources 
the appeals court said the exchange system did not amount to 
pricefixing by itself but could point to the existence of a 
conspiracy 
at various times market conditions should have caused some of 
the companies to post higher crude prices said the opinion by 
judge jerome farris posted prices did not correspond to market 
value 
farris also rejected grays conclusion that federal price 
controls and other regulations during the 197177 period made it 
impossible for the city and state to show any damages even if they 
could prove a pricefixing conspiracy 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

